# UI Theme ‚Äî PulseBMC

## What this is

This is a **diagnostic reasoning system for a hardware operator**, not a consumer app or a marketing site. Every design decision should reinforce that framing. Operators are reading this under pressure; density and clarity beat whitespace and friendliness.

## Color discipline

- **Status only:** Red/amber/green are reserved for device health, test outcomes, and alert severity. Never use them decoratively.
- **Neutral by default:** Background, borders, text, and non-status UI elements use slate/zinc/gray Tailwind tokens.
- **Accent sparingly:** One accent color (blue) for interactive elements (buttons, active states, links). Not on every heading.
- **No rainbow status codes.** If you have more than three status states, they map to the same three colors with text labels differentiating.

## Typography and density

- **Hardware operators read dense dashboards.** Text size `text-sm` is the baseline for data fields; `text-xs` for metadata and labels. Do not balloon font sizes for visual comfort.
- **Monospace for identifiers.** Device IDs, error codes, component IDs, and timestamps use `font-mono`. These are hardware names, not marketing copy.
- **No marketing language.** No "Get started", "Welcome to PulseBMC", "Everything you need to monitor your fleet". Labels are operational: "Fleet status", "Last test run", "Open alerts".

## SQL bridging (mandatory)

Every MongoDB concept surfaced in the UI must be anchored to a SQL equivalent within visual proximity. Non-negotiable examples:

- `Collection` ‚Üí annotate as "‚âà SQL table" in ConceptBar or tooltip
- Pipeline stages shown in QueryTooltip ‚Üí include SQL equivalent comment above each stage
- `$match` ‚Üí label as `WHERE` in tooltips; `$group` ‚Üí `GROUP BY`; `$lookup` ‚Üí `LEFT JOIN`
- Document viewer panels ‚Üí field labels use `(embedded array ‚Äî replaces JOIN)` annotations

If a MongoDB term appears in the UI without a SQL annotation, that is a bug.

## LED and status indicators

- LED dots must be large enough to read from 1.5m away (minimum `w-3 h-3`, prefer `w-4 h-4` on fleet grid).
- Animate only on active failure: pulse animation on red/amber LEDs. Green is static.
- Always pair color with a text label. Color-only status is inaccessible and misread by colorblind operators.

## AI agent output rules

- `RootCauseCard`: hypothesis headline ‚Üí confidence bar (visual, not just a number) ‚Üí evidence list ‚Üí next steps. Never dump raw JSON as the default view.
- `WorkOrderCard`: priority badge (P1 red / P2 amber / P3 blue / P4 gray) ‚Üí title ‚Üí ordered repair steps ‚Üí safety callouts in amber. Always show the `historical_basis` line ‚Äî this is the RAG payoff moment.
- Raw JSON behind an expand toggle only. Label the toggle "View raw document" not "JSON".

## MongoDB pitch moments ‚Äî make them visible

These are the demo talking points that must be visually distinct, not buried in prose:

1. **Vector search result** ‚Äî when similar past failures are retrieved, show similarity score as a visual bar and label the section "Found via Atlas Vector Search ‚Äî semantic similarity, not keyword match".
2. **Flexible schema** ‚Äî when showing alert evidence that differs by failure type, label it "MongoDB flexible document ‚Äî field set varies by failure type. SQL would require nullable columns or EAV table."
3. **`$facet` multi-aggregation** ‚Äî when the explore page runs facets, show "5 aggregations ¬∑ 1 round-trip" as a badge on the result.
4. **SSE real-time** ‚Äî the live pulse label on the device detail page should note "MongoDB Change Stream ‚Üí SSE" not just "Live".

## Anti-patterns ‚Äî do not build these

- **Empty states with illustrations.** If there are no alerts, show "No open alerts" in text. No art.
- **Onboarding flows.** This is a demo system; operators arrive knowing the context.
- **Skeleton loaders for fast queries.** Atlas queries on this dataset are fast (<100ms). Show a minimal spinner or nothing; skeleton screens imply slowness.
- **Pagination on small datasets.** 20 devices and ~100 recent runs fit on one page. No pagination UI.
- **Tabs that hide critical data.** If a hardware operator needs to click a tab to find an alert, the layout is wrong.
